**Anti-Money Laundering (AML)

Anti-Money Laundering (AML) refers to laws and regulations designed to prevent criminals from hiding or using illegally earned money through the financial system.

Why AML is Important
Prevents financial crimes
Stops terrorism financing
Protects banks and financial institutions
Ensures transparency and trust

Stages of Money Laundering
Placement: Illegal money enters the financial system
Layering: Money is moved to hide its source
Integration: Illegal money appears legal

AML Laws in India
Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA), 2002
Launched: 2002
Came into force: 2005
Main AML law in India
Prevents money laundering and confiscates illegal assets
Applies to banks, financial institutions, and intermediaries
Related AML Measures in India
KYC (Know Your Customer) norms
Reporting of Suspicious Transactions (STRs)
Oversight by Financial Intelligence Unit – India (FIU-IND)

AML at Global Level
Financial Action Task Force (FATF)
Established: 1989
Global body that sets AML and Counter-Terrorist Financing standards
India became a FATF member in 2010
Other Global AML Milestones
Bank Secrecy Act (USA): 1970 – First major AML law
UN Conventions: Against money laundering and organized crime

AML in Digital Finance
Applied to banks, fintech companies, cryptocurrencies, and CBDCs
Uses KYC, transaction monitoring, and reporting systems
Helps prevent misuse of digital payments

Conclusion
AML laws play a crucial role in protecting the financial system by preventing illegal money flows. Strong AML frameworks in India and globally help ensure safe, transparent, and trustworthy financial operations.

